# Line endings.
#
# Without this, the committed line endings are whatever the machine that first
# added the file happened to use, and 35 files had landed as CRLF. A checkout on
# a machine with core.autocrlf=input then leaves those files permanently
# "modified" with no edit: the working tree keeps the CRLF it was given, while
# git compares it against an LF-normalized copy. That noise hid real changes and
# made `git status` untrustworthy.
#
# LF in the repository, LF on checkout, on every platform. Nothing here needs
# CRLF — there are no .bat/.cmd/.ps1 files, and Visual Studio (Runner.rc) and
# Inno Setup (.iss) both read LF fine.
* text=auto eol=lf

# Explicit rather than sniffed: git's binary detection is a heuristic, and a
# false "text" verdict would corrupt these on checkout.
*.png binary
*.jpg binary
*.jpeg binary
*.gif binary
*.webp binary
*.ico binary
*.icns binary
*.mp4 binary
*.mov binary
*.ttf binary
*.otf binary
*.woff binary
*.woff2 binary
*.zip binary
*.jar binary
*.keystore binary
*.jks binary
*.pdf binary
